  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Released in 2020 by researchers at Janelia Research Campus, this isotropic 3D electron microscopy dataset of high-glucose-treated murine pancreatic islets has accumulated 12 citations and demonstrable downstream reuse, with its most substantive uptake appearing in high-visibility venues including <em>Nature Communications</em>. The dataset serves as a foundational reference resource for cell biology investigations of beta cell ultrastructure.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset, designated jrc_mus-pancreas-1 and hosted openly on Figshare, provides isotropic three-dimensional electron microscopy imagery of isolated murine pancreatic islets subjected to high-glucose conditions. Produced by a team spanning Janelia Research Campus alongside collaborators including Michele Solimena and Andreas Mueller, it was designed to serve as a community reference resource \u2014 linked to the OpenOrganelle data portal \u2014 enabling researchers to examine organelle architecture and beta cell biology at nanoscale resolution without needing to generate their own volumetric imaging data.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset's citation record totals 12 works according to OpenAlex, and formal data citation tracking via Crossref identifies two direct dataset references: a December 2023 bioRxiv preprint and a peer-reviewed article published in <em>Nature Communications</em> in October 2024. Both works share authorship overlap with the original dataset team \u2014 notably Andreas M\u00fcller and Song Pang \u2014 and focus on the structure, interaction, and nervous connectivity of beta cell primary cilia. The <em>Nature Communications</em> article has itself attracted 20 citations, while the preprint version garnered 10, suggesting that the dataset contributed meaningfully to a line of research that has found substantial traction in the field.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The thematic trajectory of citing works is notable: although the dataset was conceived in the context of pancreatic islet biology and glucose metabolism, its downstream use has centered on cilia biology \u2014 specifically cilium ultrastructure and axoneme organization in beta cells. This points to the dataset's value as a versatile morphological reference that supports questions beyond its original framing. Contributing institutions in the citing literature include the German Center for Diabetes Research, Technische Universit\u00e4t Dresden, the Center for Systems Biology Dresden, Howard Hughes Medical Institute, and Human Technopole, reflecting an international consortium engaged in coordinated follow-on research.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Recorded platform views stand at six as reported by DataCite, and no downloads are currently logged, which likely reflects the scale and specialized nature of volumetric electron microscopy data rather than limited interest \u2014 such datasets are typically accessed and processed through dedicated portals rather than direct file downloads. The absence of broad social media or news coverage is consistent with the dataset's role as infrastructure for specialist research rather than a broadly popularized finding. Overall, jrc_mus-pancreas-1 represents a well-positioned community resource whose impact is best measured through the quality and reach of the science it has enabled.</p>",
